'''Joseph Tetteh Anang''' (born 8 June 2000) is a Ghanaian professional [[Association football|footballer]] who plays as a [[Goalkeeper (association football)|goalkeeper]] for [[League of Ireland Premier Division]] club [[St Patrick's Athletic F.C.|St Patrick's Athletic]]. A former youth international for England, he plays for the [[Ghana national football team|Ghana national team]].

==Early life==
Born in [[Teshie]], a suburb of Ghana's capital city [[Accra]],<ref name="auto"/><ref name="Joseph Anang: West Ham United keeper joins Stevenage on loan">{{cite news| title = Joseph Anang: West Ham United keeper joins Stevenage on loan| url = https://www.bbc.co.uk/sport/football/57488750| website = BBC Sport| date = 15 June 2021| accessdate = 7 August 2021}}</ref> Anang moved to England in his teenage years, following his parents leaving Ghana for a better life,<ref name="Academy quickfire questions: Joseph Anang">{{cite news| title = Academy quickfire questions: Joseph Anang| url = https://www.whufc.com/news/articles/2021/may/26-may/academy-quickfire-questions-joseph-anang| publisher = West Ham United F.C.| date = 26 May 2021| accessdate = 7 August 2021}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.theguardian.com/football/ng-interactive/2026/jun/04/world-cup-2026-complete-player-guide|title=World Cup 2026: guide to all 1,248 players|first1=Marcus|last1=Christenson|first2=David|last2=Hills|first3=Steven|last3=Bloor|first4=Garry|last4=Blight|first5=Billy|last5=Munday|date=4 June 2026|via=The Guardian}}</ref> Before playing as a goalkeeper, he played as a [[Defender (association football)#Centre-back|centre-back]].<ref name="Academy quickfire questions: Joseph Anang"/>

==Club career==
===West Ham United===
[[File:West Ham warmup Leicester away.jpeg|thumb|Anang (extreme right) warming up with [[West Ham United F.C.|West Ham United]] in 2023.]]
Anang began playing in the youth team for Danbort in his native Ghana, before moving to [[Ghana Premier League]] club [[Legon Cities FC|Wa All Stars]].<ref name="auto"/><ref>{{cite web|url=https://ghanasoccernet.com/west-ham-united-still-waiting-for-a-work-permit-for-ghanaian-goalkeeper-joseph-anang|title=West Ham United still waiting for a work permit for Ghanaian goalkeeper Joseph Anang|publisher=Ghana Soccernet|date=19 September 2017|accessdate=7 August 2021}}</ref> He went on trial with [[West Ham United F.C.|West Ham United]], ultimately signing for the club as an academy scholar in July 2017.<ref name="West Ham United – Joseph Anang">{{cite news| title = West Ham United – Joseph Anang| url = https://www.whufc.com/teams/development-squad/squad/joseph-anang| publisher = West Ham United F.C.| date = 15 June 2021| accessdate = 7 August 2021}}</ref> He had to wait until March 2018 to play for the club's under-18 team, having not gained international clearance, during which he also trained with the first team alongside goalkeeper [[Adrián (footballer)|Adrián]].<ref name="West Ham United – Joseph Anang"/> Anang signed his first professional contract with West Ham on 1 July 2018.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.whufc.com/news/articles/2018/july/01-july/anang-signs-first-pro-deal|title=Anang signs first pro deal|publisher=West Ham United F.C.|date=1 July 2018|accessdate=7 August 2021}}</ref> During his time with the club, he became close friends with fellow [[Ghanaian]] [[Mohammed Kudus]] when he signed from [[AFC Ajax|Ajax]] in 2023.<ref name="auto"/> He made five appearances in the [[EFL Trophy]] for West Ham's under-21 team.<ref name="Soccerway – Joseph Anang"/><ref name="West Ham United – Joseph Anang"/> Anang signed a new contract with West Ham on 15 December 2020, with the agreement running until the summer of 2024.<ref>{{cite news| title = Joseph Anang signs new West Ham United contract| url = https://www.whufc.com/news/articles/2020/december/15-december/joseph-anang-signs-new-west-ham-united-contract| publisher = West Ham United F.C.| date = 15 December 2020| accessdate = 8 August 2021}}</ref> He departed the club at the end of his contract in 2024, having been on the bench as an unused substitute on 32 occasions for the first team.<ref name="Soccerway – Joseph Anang"/>

====Loan to Stevenage====
Anang joined [[EFL League Two|League Two]] club [[Stevenage F.C.|Stevenage]] on a season-long [[Loan (sports)|loan]] agreement on 15 June 2021.<ref name="Joseph Anang: West Ham United keeper joins Stevenage on loan"/> He made his [[English Football League]] debut in Stevenage's 1–0 victory against [[Barrow A.F.C.|Barrow]] on 7 August 2021.<ref>{{cite news| title = Stevenage 1–0 Barrow| url = https://www.bbc.co.uk/sport/football/58036335| website = BBC Sport| date = 7 August 2021| accessdate = 7 August 2021}}</ref> Anang made 18 appearances during the first half of the [[2021–22 Stevenage F.C. season|2021–22 season]],<ref name = "2021-22">{{Soccerbase season|116289|2021|name=Joseph Anang|accessdate=4 January 2022}}</ref> before returning to West Ham in January 2022.<ref>{{cite news| title = Loan Watch: Frederik Alves features for Sunderland| url = https://www.whufc.com/news/articles/2022/january/04-january/loan-watch-frederik-alves-features-sunderland| publisher = West Ham United F.C.| date = 4 January 2022| accessdate = 4 January 2022}}</ref>

====Loan to St Patrick's Athletic====
On 28 January 2022, it was announced that Anang had signed for [[League of Ireland Premier Division]] side [[St Patrick's Athletic F.C.|St Patrick's Athletic]] on loan until the end of November, ahead of their [[2022 St Patrick's Athletic F.C. season|2022 season]], following a recommendation of the club by former [[West Ham United F.C.|West Ham United]] teammate [[Alfie Lewis]] who played for the club in 2021.<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.stpatsfc.com/news.php?id=9096|title=Goalkeeper Anang Signs On Loan!|website=www.stpatsfc.com}}</ref> On 11 February 2022, he made his debut for the club in the [[2022 President of Ireland's Cup]] against [[Shamrock Rovers F.C.|Shamrock Rovers]] at [[Tallaght Stadium]], as his side lost 5–4 on penalties after a 1–1 draw.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.the42.ie/shamrock-rovers-st-pats-report-3-5681143-Feb2022/|title=Memorable return for Jack Byrne as Shamrock Rovers beat Pat's on penalties|first=Paul|last=Fennessy|website=The42|date=11 February 2022 }}</ref> He made his league debut for the club a week later, keeping a clean sheet in a 3–0 win away to [[Derbies in the League of Ireland#Shelbourne vs St. Patrick's Athletic (Red Derby)|Dublin rivals]] [[Shelbourne F.C.|Shelbourne]] at [[Tolka Park]].<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.whufc.com/news/articles/2022/february/21-february/loan-watch-joseph-anang-keeps-clean-sheet-league-ireland|title=Loan Watch: Joseph Anang keeps clean sheet on League of Ireland debut &#124; West Ham United|website=www.whufc.com}}</ref> He made his first appearance in European football on 21 July 2022 in a 1–1 draw with Slovenian side [[NŠ Mura]] in the [[UEFA Europa Conference League]].<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.irishtimes.com/sport/soccer/2022/07/21/chris-forrester-inspires-revival-as-st-patricks-athletic-keep-the-tie-alive/|title=Chris Forrester inspires revival as St Patrick's Athletic keep the tie alive|newspaper=The Irish Times}}</ref> Anang was the penalty shootout "hero" in the second leg in [[Slovenia]] as his side won the shootout 6–5 following a 0–0 draw after extra time.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.rte.ie/sport/soccer/2022/0728/1312665-anang-the-hero-as-pats-hold-nerve-in-penalty-shoot-out/|title=Anang the hero as Pat's hold nerve in penalty shootout|first=Dave|last=Donnelly|date=28 July 2022|via=www.rte.ie}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.the42.ie/st-pats-cska-sofia-preview-5832226-Aug2022/?amp=1|title=TheJournal.ie - Praise for West Ham youngster starring at Pat's ahead of another big European night for Irish football|website=www.the42.ie|date=4 August 2022 }}</ref> Anang's loan was cut short in August 2022 with Pat's manager [[Tim Clancy]] stating that Anang refused to travel to Bulgaria for a [[UEFA Europa Conference League]] fixture against [[PFC CSKA Sofia|CSKA Sofia]] unless he was allowed to end his loan spell early after the club exited the competition.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.the42.ie/joseph-anang-pats-5841040-Aug2022/?amp=1|title=TheJournal.ie - 'He wouldn't travel to Bulgaria unless we agreed to let him go' - Clancy disappointed with manner of Anang exit|website=www.the42.ie|date=15 August 2022 }}</ref>

====Loan to Derby County====
On 14 August 2022, Anang was recalled from his loan at St Patrick's Athletic and sent to [[Derby County F.C.|Derby County]] on a season-long loan.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.dcfc.co.uk/news/2022/08/goalkeeper-anang-secures-derby-loan-switch|title=GOALKEEPER ANANG SECURES DERBY LOAN SWITCH|website=www.dcfc.co.uk}}</ref><ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.bbc.com/sport/football/62547363|title=West Ham goalkeeper Anang joins Derby on loan|work=BBC Sport }}</ref> He suffered a 'small arm fracture' in training shortly after signing for the club, an injury that kept him out of action for several months.<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.derbytelegraph.co.uk/sport/football/football-news/derby-county-injury-news-anang-7498373|title=Derby County injury update as timeframe set ahead of West Brom clash|newspaper=Derbyshirelive |date=23 August 2022|via=www.derbytelegraph.co.uk}}</ref> The loan was terminated in January 2023.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.whufc.com/news/joseph-anang-returns-derby-county-loan|title=Joseph Anang returns from Derby County loan &#124; West Ham United F.C.|website=www.whufc.com}}</ref>

====Return to West Ham United====
On 5 June 2024, West Ham United confirmed that Anang would depart the club upon the expiration of his contract at the end of the month.<ref>{{cite web |date=5 June 2024 |title=Ogbonna and Anang to leave West Ham United |url=https://www.whufc.com/news/ogbonna-and-anang-leave-west-ham-united |access-date=6 June 2024 |website=West Ham United F.C.}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web |date=5 June 2024 |title=West Ham United news: Angelo Ogbonna to leave Hammers when contract expires |url=https://www.bbc.com/sport/football/articles/ceqq5656v4yo |access-date=6 June 2024 |website=[[BBC Sport]] |language=en-GB}}</ref>

===Return to St Patrick's Athletic===
On 24 June 2024, Anang returned to his old club [[St Patrick's Athletic F.C.|St Patrick's Athletic]] on a two-and-a-half-year contract, becoming recently appointed manager [[Stephen Kenny (football manager)|Stephen Kenny]]'s first signing at the club.<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.stpatsfc.com/news.php?id=9638|title=Anang Returns To Richmond|website=www.stpatsfc.com}}</ref> Anang featured in all 6 of the club's [[UEFA Conference League]] games during the summer of 2024, as they beat [[FC Vaduz|Vaduz]] of [[Liechtenstein]] and [[Sabah FC (Azerbaijan)|Sabah]] of [[Azerbaijan]] before a narrow 2–0 defeat on aggregate against [[Turkey|Turkish]] side [[İstanbul Başakşehir F.K.|İstanbul Başakşehir]] in the Play-Off Round of the competition.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.uefa.com/uefaconferenceleague/clubs/players/250174123--joseph-anang/matches/|title=Joseph Anang &#124; Matches|website=[[UEFA]]}}</ref> On 17 July 2025, Anang made the 100th appearance of his career, in a 2–0 win away to [[FC Hegelmann|Hegelmann]] in the [[UEFA Conference League]], in what was his 4th clean sheet in consecutive games.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.irishtimes.com/sport/soccer/2025/07/17/mason-melia-proves-too-hot-to-handle-as-st-patricks-athletic-see-off-hegelmann-in-lithuania/|title=Mason Melia proves too hot to handle as St Patrick's Athletic see off Hegelmann in Lithuania|website=The Irish Times}}</ref> Anang finished the season with 18 sheets in 36 games, the most in the league, helping his side to the best defensive record in the league and a 5th place overall.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.fotmob.com/players/963812/joseph-anang|title=Joseph Anang - stats, career and market value|website=FotMob}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.the42.ie/stephen-kenny-st-patricks-athletic-8-6862375-Nov2025/|title='We've definitely fallen short of our expectations' - Stephen Kenny on fifth-place finish|first=David|last=Sneyd|date=1 November 2025|website=The 42}}</ref> On 8 February 2026, Anang was named Man of the Match in the opening game of the [[2026 St Patrick's Athletic F.C. season|2026 season]] after making some excellent 1v1 saves in a 0–0 draw with [[Bohemian F.C.|Bohemians]] at the [[Aviva Stadium]].<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.rte.ie/sport/soccer/2026/0208/1557329-anang-stands-tall-as-bohs-and-pats-share-the-spoils/|title=Anang stands tall as Bohs and Pat's share the spoils|first=Paul|last=Buttner|date=8 February 2026|via=www.rte.ie}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://ghanaweb.com/GhanaHomePage/SportsArchive/Joseph-Anang-shines-with-Man-of-the-Match-performance-in-Irish-League-opener-2020962|title= Joseph Anang with Man of the Match performance in Irish League opener|website=ghanaweb.com}}</ref> On 6 March 2026, Anang made his 100th appearance for the club in a 3–2 win away to rivals [[Shelbourne F.C.|Shelbourne]], having let 44 clean sheets and conceeding an average of just 0.98 goals per game in those appearances.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://ghanasoccernet.com/ghana-goalkeeper-joseph-anang-marks-100th-appearance-for-st-patricks-athletic|title=Ghana goalkeeper Joseph Anang marks 100th appearance for St. Patrick's Athletic|date=8 March 2026|website=GhanaSoccernet}}</ref> The following week, he saved a penalty from ex-teammate [[Mark Doyle (footballer)|Mark Doyle]] in the 60th minute to stop [[Drogheda United F.C.|Drogheda United]] from taking a 2–1 lead as his side then went on to win 4–1 at [[Richmond Park (football ground)|Richmond Park]].<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.the42.ie/st-pats-drogheda-united-match-report-6984730-Mar2026/|title=St Pat’s come from behind to dismantle Drogheda|first=Paul|last=O'Hehir|date=13 March 2026|website=The 42}}</ref>

==International career==
===England youth career===
Anang represented England at [[England national under-20 football team|under-20]] level,<ref name="Joseph Anang: West Ham United keeper joins Stevenage on loan"/> making his debut as a 79th-minute substitute in a 3–0 victory against [[Iceland national football team|Iceland]] under-20s on 19 November 2019.<ref name="West Ham United – Joseph Anang"/><ref>{{cite news| title = England U20 3–0 Iceland U20| url = https://uk.soccerway.com/matches/2019/11/19/world/under-20-friendlies/england-youth/iceland-u20/3370643/| publisher = Soccerway| date = 19 November 2019| accessdate = 7 August 2021}}</ref> In October 2024, Anang spoke on his ambition to represent the nation of his birth, revealing that he had held conversations with the [[Ghana national football team|Ghana]] camp for a couple of years about a call up, saying ''"I'm just putting in the work and waiting for a call-up, we've been speaking the last two years but I was at West Ham as a No 3 and not playing. They might look at me more now and, hopefully in the future, you never know."''<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.irishmirror.ie/sport/soccer/soccer-news/joseph-anang-makes-bold-st-34011617|title=Joseph Anang makes bold St Pat's predication for next season|first=Paul|last=O'Hehir|date=31 October 2024|website=Irish Mirror}}</ref>

===Ghana senior career===
On 26 May 2025, Anang received his first call up to the [[Ghana national football team|Ghana national team]], for their games against [[Nigeria national football team|Nigeria]] and [[Trinidad and Tobago national football team|Trinidad and Tobago]] in the [[2025 Unity Cup]] in [[London]].<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.ghanafa.org/otto-addo-names-squad-for-unity-cup-2025|title=Otto Addo names squad for Unity Cup 2025|first=Ghana Football|last=Association|website=www.ghanafa.org}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.independent.ie/sport/soccer/league-of-ireland/st-pats-keeper-joseph-anang-set-for-international-bow-after-ghana-call-up/a623493962.html|title=St Pat's keeper Joseph Anang set for international bow after Ghana call-up|date=26 May 2025|website=www.independent.ie}}</ref> On 12 October 2025, he was part of the matchday squad as they confirmed qualification to the [[2026 FIFA World Cup]] following a 1–0 win at home to [[Comoros national football team|Comoros]], earning his club St Patrick's Athletic hundreds of thousands of [[Euro]] in the process.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.rte.ie/sport/soccer/2025/1012/1538139-wc-qualifying-scots-edge-belarus-to-hit-group-summit/|title=WC qualifying: Scots edge Belarus, Faroes shock Czechia|date=12 October 2025|via=www.rte.ie}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.irishmirror.ie/sport/soccer/soccer-news/shamrock-rovers-st-patricks-athletic-36068317|title=Shamrock Rovers and St Patrick’s Athletic set for huge FIFA World Cup windfall|first=Mark|last=McCadden|date=14 October 2025|website=Irish Mirror}}</ref> On 14 November 2025, Anang made his [[Ghana national football team|Ghana]] debut in a friendly game away to [[Japan national football team|Japan]] in the [[Kirin Cup Soccer#2025 Kirin Cup Soccer|2025 Kirin Cup]].<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.bbc.com/sport/football/live/cg7npn5r4x1t|title=Japan vs Ghana: Friendlies stats & head-to-head|website=BBC Sport}}</ref>

In June 2026, he was named to Ghana's squad for the [[2026 World Cup]].<ref>https://www.independent.ie/sport/soccer/league-of-ireland/st-pats-goalkeeper-joseph-anang-makes-ghanas-world-cup-squad/a/154753825.html</ref>

